Plate Saver is a stackable modular shelving system to save space and seal full sized (11") plates of food in the refrigerator. This project was made in SketchUp and then exported to STL files. For more info watch the following video http://youtu.be/5lBztSRltd4
Designed a desktop stand for my new Moto X 2nd gen. And now you can print one too! Prints in 2 parts + right angle USB cable.

Print both TOP and BOTTOM pieces at a decent resolution. Line the insides of the TOP piece with thin (.063" / 1.5mm) foam. I use "Silly Winks / Funky Foam" adhesive-back foam, available at most craft stores. This ensures the foam, not the plastic, touches your phone. Phone will fit without it but won't be as snug. Obtain a right-angle micro USB cable: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001AR4NC8/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 ...and wedge it into the base. Snake the cable through the channel and out the back. Place the TOP on the BOTTOM - using the posts to align it - and insert your phone to make sure the USB fits correctly. Once it does, take the TOP off and put a bit of glue around the USB plug to secure it in place. Finally, super-glue the TOP to the BOTTOM and enjoy!

The Kavetto tool holder system uses a set of hard points (Kavetto_Mounts) that can be attached to the chassis of the Replicator 2 and 2X, and other printers that use the same construction, though the set has only been tested on Replicators. Note: Installation requires the purchase of M5x14 bolts to replace the stock bolts, and are available from McMaster Here: http://www.mcmaster.com/#95263A360 Once the mounts are installed, the tool keepers can be attached in any configuration that is desired. The latches that are printed with the Mounts file are press fit around the bolt hole, and are coded R and L for Right and Left when facing the mount. The R and L markings should be on the inside, and not viewable after installation to ensure proper function. The latches can be rotated down, where they will snap into place and prevent the attachments from disengaging accidentally. The attachments include the following. • The Fan accepts most small files, markers, clam knives, Dremel® bits, and screwdrivers. • The Box can accommodate flashlights, toothbrushes, and other miscellaneous tools • The Hook comes in handy for rags or tools with lanyards. • The Spooler holds a spool of filament, and is meant for the two upper most holes on the back of the printer, where two Spoolers can be installed without interfering with the spools in use. The Spooler is not made for installation on the front of the machine.

No support material is required for any of the Kavetto Tool Sets. The Kavetto_Tool_Mounts file should be printed on raft. The other files are accompanied by helper disks that are attached so that no raft is required.

description.text: Are you always forgetting what you have left in the refrigerator? Don't you wish there was an easier way to remember what you need to pick up at the store? Using this device you can alleviate the stress of being caught without food stores when you really need them. Names of essential food items are molded into the hexagonal plastic pieces grafted to magnets that remain affixed to their base inside the fridge until their particular food has been used up. They then can be detached from their base and place outside on the fridge's surface in order to alert the members of the household of the missing items. This way you can remember to add them to your shopping list, and pick them up at the store. Please attach it using  1/2? round magnet and double sided tape.

title: A Simple Filament Holder for 48mm Spools

description.text:
I used the legs from mscourch's version, but remade the spool ends for a 48mm ID spool.  I also increased the leg area on the ground for better support.  
Update: Added a spoolend for 38mm ID spools for Signstek filament that I picked up recently.  
Update2: Added 71mm spoolend for new Sainsmart filament, they changed their spool end design

Print two of Spoolend.stl (For 48mm ID spools) or Spoolend 38.stl (For 38mm ID spools) and two of Spoolholder.stl.  Clean support from Spoolends and insert one 608ZZ bearing in each side.  Should be a press fit.  I used a vice to gently force the bearing in.  Use 5/16" threaded rod and some wingnuts or similar.  I used a 6mm allen wrench for now.

Form-fitting cover for a DSC WS4939 Alarm fob, so that it doesn't activate my ear-splitting house alarm from my pocket. It may just have saved my hearing.

No more reaching to the back of the fridge, no more taking eggs out of the fridge and placing it on the counter to roll off, as the whole egg cradle is removable. Future editions might add 2 or 3 cradles next to each other to increase the total amount of eggs storable.

This is a model stand that I built to display the Tie Interceptor model (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5549) that I printed out. It uses the Global Dynamics Logo by Modelmaker and does some modification: resizing, rotation and copying to create an open pyramid where one can display a model. The current version of the file only has a 3mm hole in the top so you can use any piece of filament that you want to adjust the height to.

Print it, sand it (or otherwise get a smooth surface), tape the top portion that is not part of the Global Dynamics logo and then paint it using metallic gold paint.  Apply several thin coats allowing each coat to dry before applying the next coat.
When ready select your favorite object, drill an appropriate sized hole (~3mm) in it and mount it on the stand.

This is my second lasercut project, after a few shadowpuppets I produced. A cardboard wine rack. Holes are 3.5" in diameter -- too small for Magnums, but about right for a standard 750mL bottle. As an added bonus, a variety of stars and coasters are cut out of the waste cardboard. Inspired by robyward's Assymetric Wine Rack http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4965 -- but I modified the design to fit the limitations of my 12x24 build materials. TODO for version 2:
  • make the holes bigger. 3.6" would allow some larger bottles to fit.
  • ditch the side holes, they aren't secure enough for bottles.
  • make the struts wider.
Lasercut 6 copies of this image out of thick (1/4"-ish) cardboard, each 12"x24".  Each copy produces one upright part and two connector struts.  Assemble.

This box is for hive game with extensions
(2 sets of 14 figures). Openscad source also added. May be customized. UPD: Just added the scribe 'HIVE' on the cover.
It is intended to be printed with dualstude. V2: changed the sizes a little bit. And also added the hole on the bottom of the box (because it is quite hard to put figures there and pull them back without a hole for air)

No special instructions.
Just keep in mind that it contains big solid plate. So, when printing with materials like ABS or Nylon take care of the fact that it can unstick. If you don't have dualstruder, just add 'cover' and 'scribe' into the plate and assign one and same extruder to both. You'll get one solid thing. OR just print the cover as is.

comments.text:

(when using such way you don't need the lid)

description.text: Much like another user (jamesarm97), I was in the mood for donuts, so I ended up doing a quick design while the dough was rising so I could cut the donuts into shape. I was originally had the same idea as jamesarm97 with a single unit, but decided to separate the parts so I could make "munchkins" as well. In either case, this is a 100mm outer ring with a 40mm inner ring as separate parts. Inspiration for the donuts came from: http://youtu.be/aqtTb62RoK8 and I can't wait to try them later tonight! Dough is still rising and cutter is printing as I type! Cheers!
Follow the YouTube instructions on how to make the dough... print this cutter... and enjoy your treat!

description.text: A friend had a bag to carry equipment for a couples' bowling league, but needed something to keep the balls from rolling all over. I made this so two could be bolted to a thin board with standard 1/4" bolts.

Print it out. Even supporting a bowling ball, it has enough area that it requires very little infill. I used 8%. I had problems with warping when I used a 45 degree infill once it got to the beginning of the 'dish' since it would have bands of solid infill pulling the corners towards each other. If you do the infill at 90 degrees, it goes from the middle of the sides, so the corners can stay planted and square. These are functional rather than for decoration, so I went with a standard 0.27mm layer height at 120 mm/s.

title: Pump sump/reservoir for Hot end coolant.

description.text: Uses aquarium pump: http://www.dx.com/p/334988 to push the water. My first print leaked slightly, the wall thickness of the reservoir is 2mm. Try setting a wider nozzle size than you are actually using and run the printer a bit slower to ensure you can push the extra volume of filament, This will build much better inter-layer bonding. Set 100% fill also. If using a tall rostock, mount within 500mm or less of the top of the water tubes to help priming. You will probably need to prime the pump as the way I have it oriented, it will seal against self priming. Put someprotective plastic sheet down and towel and siphon to start then seal up.

author: fluidity

title: Printrbot Top Joinder w Nut Retainer & Y offset

description.text: edit/ Added SCAD file /edit Based on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:23038, but with retained nut, and clearance for high-Z. TheGrum's version was fine, and I liked the Printrbot logo. A while ago I was learning OpenSCAD so decided to do a version for 8mm threaded rod and with the nut retained (also has no bridging). See the v3 stl & the red one in the photos. It did improve the smoothness of the prints. See the close-up, the red one was printed without a joinder, the white one with the red fitted, much crisper edge, but I found the stepper crashed into it at high Z. So I did another design moved back on the Y axis, see the v4 stl, the white ones in the photos.

Remember it is NOT a handle. Print a little chunky (I did 2 perimiters & 20%), my first print(at 1 perimiter &10% fill) split 1/2 way up the threaded rod level when I forced the rod. I had to drill out a small amount in the 8mm holes, the nut trap was fine for the nuts I have. Insert the top threaded rod into a drill chuck to easily move them into place.
Move Z high so the ends are in the right place (in case they are slightly misaligned). Mount one end on the Z rod, then align the other by spinning it until it lines up with the other Z rod. Consider whether you want the threaded rod longer to potentially mount other things.

description.text:
We bought lots of white ABS with our shapercube.. Lots. But who wants
to print everything in white? After a while that got a
bit.. samey. So, an experiment, jam a coloured marker in the feedstock
inlet and see what happens. What happened was, coloured prints came
out. So the idea for the marker organ was born, a way to attached
several coloured markers to the feedstock, and pick which one, or
combination, is colouring the plastic. This is the first attempt, a simple clamp over the feedstock which
holds a single marker against it.

Note: Please don't get discouraged by the wall of text. It's not that hard, I just wanted to document it fully! Instructions: Becuase there's no de-facto standard for the shape of markers, you'll
have to measure your marker and change the openscad model to fit.
Don't worry, it's pretty easy. If you want to be lazy, you can just
get the exact markers I used for this. You can also change the size of the hardware you'll use to put it
together. Since it's currently set up for M6 bolts with square nuts
(because I had lots of them on hand), and because you need to modify
for marker size anyway, this is probably a good idea. If you want to get the same markers I'm using, they appear to be
http://www.staples.co.uk/office-supplies/writing-correction/writing-instruments/markers/permanent-markers/staples-permanent-and-dry-proof-markers/permanent-markers-4-pack-assorted
. Oddly, this doesn't match the number on the packaging, which says
"item #11090". Open the .scad file in your favorite text editor. First, the bolt
size: change the line that says "bolt_dia = 6;" to list the diameter
of your bolts, in mm. (Don't add an extra bit for clearance; you want
one of the bolts to cut it's own thread as you put it in.) Make sure
you haven't accidentally removed the semicolon on the end of the line. Measure the diameter of the part of the pen that you want to grip
(just above the actual tip), in milimeters and put it in where it says
"pen_holder_bottom_id = 8.5;". As above, make sure you
don't delete the semicolon. You want this to be a tight fit, but not
so tight that you can't get the marker in at all. If you get it wrong
the first time, you can always print another one. Next, measure the length of the part of the pen that you want to grip
-- the part that is no wider then the pen_holder_bottom_id. You
should include space for the tip of the marker in this measurement as
well. Err on the side of making it shorter then neccessary -- it
needs to be long enough to get a good grip, but not so long as to keep
the tip from actually touching the feedstock. Next, run openscad. Do a file/open to get your file, then
design/compile and render. (It's normal for that to take several
seconds.) Then design/export as stl, and do whatever you'd normally
do to print an STL file. Usage: Clamp the two parts together with bolts, with your feedstock running
through the middle. Insert your marker and clamp it in using a bolt
through the side hole. Print something!

description.text: An area of the Scottish Highlands that contains Beinn Eight and Liathach. This is an area between Loch Maree to the north/northeast and Upper Loch Torridon to the southwest/west. Constructed using 1 arcsecond resolution SRTM data from the Space Shuttle (about 2 million polygons). It was made using a new and, as yet, unreleased version of SRTM2STL. You may want to print this to be relatively small. I get warping using PLA and it gets bad when I try to print Raised Relief Maps that are big. I have had 'some' success with big maps. If you have a way to control warping you may also have better luck with big maps.

I really liked the filament holders that used bearings for the spool itself to roll on but always thought they were inefficient and did not scale well since they always involved large prints and only held a single spool. I set out to fix this using minimal printing and cheap parts. This system uses a series of spacers and clips to hold multiple spools on 2x8mm smooth rods (the cheap $3 kind from the hardware store not the nice kind used for printer axis) Filament catches pass filament up to printer through PTFE tubing and hold filament ends for quickly switching as many spools as you want! (In my case 16) Spools are easily swapped without disturbing other spools. UPDATE:
Video: http://youtu.be/BfAczR-4zKc
1.3 Added Filament catch system for easily switching between many filaments
1.2 Added cabinet rail holder and more photos.
1.1 Added smaller spacer to save print time when making lots of them. Credit to LittleDangerous for the C clip

Sandwitch a standard 608 skate bearing between two spacers on one of the smooth rods and put a clip on each side, (alternatively, print spacers with 105% flow rate and the spacers themselves should be tight on the rod.)  do this twice per spool per rod (a total of 4x per spool) I find that if I keep these assemblies  slightly looser the spools spin better. Slide your bearing assemblies along the rail to account for different spool sizes. Insert small (or long) lengths of PTFE tubing through holes in filament catches and feed filament up through to extruder as shown in pictures. Use Dremel buffing bits to clean dust from filament.(Optional) Enjoy easy filament switching!

description.text:
OpenSCAD model generates a stacked set of Plexiglass slices that can be assembled into a small box. More info on my web site:
http://ph-elec.com/archives/openscad-stacked-plexiglass-enclosure/ YouTube Video:
http://youtu.be/Cy97yn67pjU

Use a laser cutter to cut all the pieces out.
Use acrylic glue to seal the top and bottom covers onto the core slices.  The case can then be opened like a clam shell.
Larger cavities can be created using more core slices.
Everything is a parameter in the OpenSCAD source code.
